
Act like an API endpoint that validates and corrects a UML class model.

You are given:
1) original requirements
2) extracted entities
3) inferred relations

Original requirements:
'{{ requirements }}'

Entities:
{% for entity in entities_result.entities %}
- {{ entity.name }} ({{ entity.type }})
  Attributes:
  {% for attr in entity.attributes %}
  - {{ attr.name }}: {{ attr.type }}
  {% endfor %}
{% endfor %}

Relations:
{% for relation in relations_result.relations %}
- {{ relation.source }} -> {{ relation.target }} ({{ relation.type }})
  multiplicity: {{ relation.multiplicity.source if relation.multiplicity else "1" }} .. {{ relation.multiplicity.target if relation.multiplicity else "*" }}
{% endfor %}

Check for missing entities, redundant entities, missing relations, and obvious multiplicity/type issues.
Return a corrected final model.

Respond with a JSON object that matches this schema:
{
  "issues_found": [
    {
      "issue_type": "missing_relation",
      "description": "What was wrong",
      "suggestion": "Suggested fix"
    }
  ],
  "corrected_entities": [
    {
      "name": "ClassName",
      "type": "class",
      "attributes": [
        {
          "name": "attribute_name",
          "type": "str|int|bool|datetime|enum",
          "enum": null,
          "derived": false,
          "description": null,
          "body": null
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
  "corrected_relations": [
    {
      "source": "SourceClassName",
      "target": "TargetClassName",
      "type": "association|composition|generalization|dependency",
      "multiplicity": {
        "source": "1",
        "target": "*"
      },
      "label": ""
    }
  ]
}

Rules:
- Return only JSON. No prose, no markdown, no code fences.
- corrected_relations endpoints must match corrected_entities names.
- If no issues are found, return the same model with issues_found as [].
